<DocsLayout title="Agent Specification">
  <h1>Agent Specification</h1>
  <p>
    This document is the authoritative technical reference for the EncodeSwarmr Agent. It covers installation, configuration, internal state machine, offline operation, task execution, GPU management, security, logging, and the upgrade strategy.
  </p>
  <p>
    Agents are the worker processes that accept encoding jobs from the Controller, execute them using local encoder binaries, and stream progress back over gRPC with mTLS. Agents run on both Windows Server and Linux and are designed to survive controller connectivity loss without losing work.
  </p>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Each agent is a single statically-linked Go binary with no external runtime dependencies (CGO is disabled). On startup it:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>Loads <code>agent.yaml</code> and merges any environment variable overrides.</li>
    <li>Opens (or creates) its local SQLite offline journal.</li>
    <li>Probes for GPU hardware if <code>gpu.enabled: true</code>.</li>
    <li>Dials the controller over mTLS, presenting its client certificate for mutual authentication.</li>
    <li>Registers itself and waits for administrator approval.</li>
    <li>Once approved, enters the polling loop and accepts job assignments.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Installation &amp; Configuration</h2>

  <h3>Windows — Prerequisites</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Requirement</th><th>Minimum</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Windows Server</td><td>2019 (1809)</td><td>2022 recommended; Windows 10/11 supported for dev use</td></tr>
      <tr><td>CPU</td><td>4 cores</td><td>8+ recommended for parallel encode jobs</td></tr>
      <tr><td>RAM</td><td>8 GiB</td><td>16 GiB recommended when using GPU encoders</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Disk (work_dir)</td><td>50 GiB free</td><td>Temporary encode workspace; SSD strongly recommended</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Network</td><td>1 Gbps</td><td>10 Gbps recommended for large media files on NAS</td></tr>
      <tr><td>GPU driver (NVIDIA)</td><td>531.x+</td><td>Required for NVENC hardware encoding</td></tr>
      <tr><td>GPU driver (AMD)</td><td>23.Q1+</td><td>Required for AMF hardware encoding</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Windows — Service Installation</h3>
  <pre><code># Run as Administrator

# GUI installer (recommended for interactive setups)
EncodeSwarmr-Agent-Setup.exe

# Unattended / scripted install
encodeswarmr-agent.exe install ^
  --controller controller.example.com:9443 ^
  --token &lt;enrollment-token&gt; ^
  --work-dir "D:\EncodeWork" ^
  --name "WIN-ENCODE-01"

# Verify and start
sc query EncodeSwarmrAgent
net start EncodeSwarmrAgent

# Uninstall
net stop EncodeSwarmrAgent
encodeswarmr-agent.exe uninstall</code></pre>

