  <h3>Linux — Service Installation</h3>
  <pre><code># Download and run the convenience install script
curl -fsSL https://github.com/badskater/encodeswarmr/releases/latest/download/install-agent.sh | sudo bash

# Or install the package manually (Debian/Ubuntu)
sudo dpkg -i encodeswarmr-agent_amd64.deb

# Or on RHEL/Rocky
sudo dnf install -y ./encodeswarmr-agent_amd64.rpm

# Register with the controller (writes certs and agent.yaml)
sudo encodeswarmr-agent register \
  --controller controller.example.com:9443 \
  --token &lt;enrollment-token&gt;

# Enable and start
sudo systemctl enable --now encodeswarmr-agent

# Follow the log
sudo journalctl -u encodeswarmr-agent -f</code></pre>

  <h3>Full Configuration Reference</h3>
  <p>See the <a href="/docs/configuration">Configuration Reference</a> page for the fully annotated <code>agent.yaml</code>. A minimal working example:</p>
  <pre><code>controller:
  address: "controller.example.com:9443"
  tls:
    cert: /etc/encodeswarmr/certs/agent.crt
    key:  /etc/encodeswarmr/certs/agent.key
    ca:   /etc/encodeswarmr/certs/ca.crt

agent:
  hostname: "linux-encode-01"
  work_dir: /var/lib/encodeswarmr/work
  log_dir:  /var/log/encodeswarmr
  cleanup_on_success: true
  keep_failed_work_dir: true

tools:
  ffmpeg:  /usr/local/bin/ffmpeg
  ffprobe: /usr/local/bin/ffprobe

gpu:
  enabled: true
  vendor:  auto

allowed_shares:
  - /mnt/nas/media

logging:
  level:  info
  format: json</code></pre>

  <h2>State Machine</h2>
  <p>
    The agent is modelled as an explicit finite state machine. Each state has a well-defined set of valid transitions. Invalid transitions (e.g. jumping from IDLE to REPORTING) are rejected with a panic in debug builds and a logged error in production.
  </p>
  <pre><code>
  ┌──────────────────┐
  │  INITIALISING    │  Load config → open SQLite → probe GPU
  └────────┬─────────┘
           │ success
           ▼
  ┌──────────────────┐
  │  REGISTERING     │  Dial controller gRPC (mTLS handshake)
  └────────┬─────────┘
           │ connected
           ▼
  ┌──────────────────┐
  │  PENDING         │  Awaiting administrator approval in UI
  └────────┬─────────┘
           │ approved
           ▼
  ┌──────────────────┐       connectivity lost
  │  IDLE            │─────────────────────────────────────────┐
  └────────┬─────────┘                                         │
           │ job assigned                                      │
           ▼                                                   │
  ┌──────────────────┐                                         │
  │  PREPARING       │  Validate paths, tools, work dir        │
  └────────┬─────────┘                                         ▼
           │ ready                               ┌──────────────────┐
           ▼                                     │  OFFLINE         │
  ┌──────────────────┐                           │                  │
  │  ENCODING        │  Spawn encoder, stream    │  Journal buffers │
  └────────┬─────────┘  progress via gRPC        │  state; back-off │
           │ done                                │  reconnect loop  │
           ▼                                     └────────┬─────────┘
  ┌──────────────────┐                                    │ reconnected
  │  REPORTING       │  Upload metadata, clean up         │
  └────────┬─────────┘                                    │
           │ complete                                      │
           └──────────────────────► IDLE ◄────────────────┘

  Error paths:
    PREPARING  → IDLE  (validation failure; job returned to queue)
    ENCODING   → IDLE  (encoder crash; job marked failed)
    REPORTING  → IDLE  (upload failure; retried on reconnect)
  </code></pre>

  <h2>Offline Operation</h2>

  <h3>Principles</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>An agent that loses connectivity to the controller continues encoding its current job to completion.</li>
    <li>All state changes (job start, progress snapshots, job completion/failure) are written to the local SQLite journal before being sent to the controller.</li>
    <li>On reconnect, the agent replays any unacknowledged journal entries to the controller in order.</li>
    <li>The controller deduplicates replayed events using the event UUID stored in the journal.</li>
    <li>There is no data loss as long as the agent's disk is intact.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>SQLite Journal Schema</h3>
  <pre><code>-- Core event log: every state change is appended here.
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS events (
    id          INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
    uuid        TEXT    NOT NULL UNIQUE,   -- idempotency key sent to controller
    event_type  TEXT    NOT NULL,          -- job_started | progress | job_done | job_failed
    job_id      TEXT    NOT NULL,
    payload     BLOB    NOT NULL,          -- serialised protobuf EventPayload
    created_at  INTEGER NOT NULL,          -- Unix timestamp (seconds)
    synced_at   INTEGER                    -- NULL until acknowledged by controller
);

-- Checkpoint: last confirmed position per job for progress dedup.
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS sync_checkpoints (
    job_id          TEXT    PRIMARY KEY,
    last_event_uuid TEXT    NOT NULL,
    updated_at      INTEGER NOT NULL
);

-- Persisted job context so the agent can resume after a process restart.
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS active_jobs (
    job_id       TEXT    PRIMARY KEY,
    assignment   BLOB    NOT NULL,         -- serialised protobuf JobAssignment
    state        TEXT    NOT NULL,         -- PREPARING | ENCODING | REPORTING
    pid          INTEGER,                  -- encoder process PID (NULL if not running)
    started_at   INTEGER NOT NULL,
    updated_at   INTEGER NOT NULL
);</code></pre>

  <h3>Sync Flow</h3>
  <pre><code>Agent reconnects to controller
         │
         ▼
  Open gRPC SyncStream
         │
         ▼
  SELECT * FROM events
   WHERE synced_at IS NULL
   ORDER BY id ASC
         │
         ▼  (for each unsynced event)
  Send event to controller
         │
         ├── controller ACKs ──► UPDATE events SET synced_at = now() WHERE uuid = ?
         │
         └── controller NACKs ─► log warning; retry after back-off

  After all events synced:
         │
         ▼
  Resume normal operation (IDLE polling loop)</code></pre>

  <h2>Task Execution Detail</h2>

  <h3>Pre-Execution Validation</h3>
  <p>Before spawning the encoder process, the agent validates:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Path whitelist check</strong> — every input and output path in the job assignment must be prefixed by an entry in <code>allowed_shares</code>. Jobs that fail this check are rejected and returned to the queue.</li>
    <li><strong>Tool availability</strong> — the agent verifies that all binaries referenced by the encoding template (<code>ffmpeg</code>, <code>x265</code>, etc.) exist and are executable.</li>
    <li><strong>Disk space</strong> — the agent checks that <code>work_dir</code> has at least 110% of the estimated output size free.</li>
    <li><strong>GPU availability</strong> — if the template requests GPU encoding and the agent's GPU is busy or VRAM is exhausted, the job is returned to the queue for reassignment.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Script Location and Execution</h3>
  <p>
    The controller bundles the encode script inside the <code>JobAssignment</code> protobuf message. The agent writes it to a temporary file inside the job's work directory before execution.
  </p>
  <p>Protobuf message (simplified):</p>
  <pre><code>message JobAssignment &#123;
  string   job_id         = 1;
  string   template_id    = 2;
  string   input_path     = 3;
  string   output_path    = 4;
  bytes    script         = 5;  // raw encode script content
  string   script_name    = 6;  // filename hint, e.g. "encode.bat" or "encode.sh"
  map&lt;string,string&gt; variables = 7;  // template variable substitutions
  GpuSpec  gpu            = 8;
  int64    estimated_size_bytes = 9;
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h3>Job Working Directory Structure</h3>
  <pre><code>&#123;work_dir&#125;/
└── &#123;job_id&#125;/
    ├── encode.bat          # (Windows) or encode.sh (Linux) — written by agent
    ├── input/              # Symlink or junction to the source path
    ├── output/             # Encoder writes output here; agent moves to output_path
    ├── tmp/                # Intermediate files (e.g. x265 2-pass stats)
    └── logs/
        ├── stdout.log      # Encoder stdout
        └── stderr.log      # Encoder stderr</code></pre>

  <h3>Process Execution (Go)</h3>
  <pre><code>// Simplified from internal/agent/executor.go

func (e *Executor) run(ctx context.Context, job *JobContext) error &#123;
    scriptPath := filepath.Join(job.WorkDir, job.Assignment.ScriptName)
    if err := os.WriteFile(scriptPath, job.Assignment.Script, 0700); err != nil &#123;
        return fmt.Errorf("write script: %w", err)
    &#125;

    var cmd *exec.Cmd
    switch runtime.GOOS &#123;
    case "windows":
        // Run inside cmd.exe with /D (disable AutoRun) and restricted environment
        cmd = exec.CommandContext(ctx, "cmd.exe", "/D", "/C", scriptPath)
    default:
        cmd = exec.CommandContext(ctx, "/bin/bash", "-eu", scriptPath)
    &#125;

    cmd.Dir = job.WorkDir
    cmd.Env = e.buildEnv(job)   // PATH + template variables only; no inherited env

    stdoutPipe, _ := cmd.StdoutPipe()
    stderrPipe, _ := cmd.StderrPipe()

    if err := cmd.Start(); err != nil &#123;
        return fmt.Errorf("start encoder: %w", err)
    &#125;
    job.PID = cmd.Process.Pid
    e.journal.SavePID(job.JobID, job.PID)

    go e.parseProgress(ctx, job, stdoutPipe)
    go e.teeLog(job, stderrPipe, job.StderrLog)

    return cmd.Wait()
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h3>Progress Parsing</h3>
  <p>
    The agent parses encoder stdout in real time to extract progress metrics. Parsed values are sent to the controller via the gRPC <code>ReportProgress</code> stream and displayed in the web UI.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Encoder</th><th>Parsed Field</th><th>Pattern / Source</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>ffmpeg</td><td>frame, fps, speed, time</td><td><code>frame=\s*(\d+).*fps=\s*([\d.]+).*time=([\d:.]+).*speed=\s*([\d.]+)x</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>x265</td><td>frames encoded, eta, bitrate</td><td><code>(\d+) frames.*eta\s+([\d:]+).*(\d+\.\d+)\s*kb/s</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>x264</td><td>frames, fps, eta</td><td><code>(\d+)/(\d+)\s+frames.*(\d+\.\d+)\s+fps.*eta\s+([\d:]+)</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>SVT-AV1</td><td>Encoding frame, fps</td><td><code>Encoding frame\s+(\d+).*(\d+\.\d+)\s+fps</code></td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    Unrecognised output lines are written verbatim to <code>stdout.log</code> and streamed to the controller log tail, but do not cause progress parse failures.
  </p>

  <h2>GPU Detection &amp; Monitoring</h2>

  <h3>Detection</h3>
  <p>
    When <code>gpu.vendor: auto</code>, the agent runs the following probes in order at startup. The first successful probe wins and sets the active vendor.
  </p>
  <pre><code>// Simplified from internal/agent/gpu/detect.go

func Detect() (*GPUInfo, error) &#123;
    // 1. NVIDIA — check for nvidia-smi or NVML
    if info, err := probeNVIDIA(); err == nil &#123;
        return info, nil
    &#125;

    // 2. AMD — check for amf-info or rocm-smi
    if info, err := probeAMD(); err == nil &#123;
        return info, nil
    &#125;

    // 3. Intel — check for vainfo (VA-API) or intel_gpu_top
    if info, err := probeIntel(); err == nil &#123;
        return info, nil
    &#125;

    return &GPUInfo&#123;Vendor: VendorNone&#125;, nil
&#125;

func probeNVIDIA() (*GPUInfo, error) &#123;
    out, err := exec.Command("nvidia-smi",
        "--query-gpu=name,memory.total,driver_version",
        "--format=csv,noheader,nounits").Output()
    if err != nil &#123;
        return nil, err
    &#125;
    // parse CSV output ...
    return info, nil
&#125;

func probeAMD() (*GPUInfo, error) &#123;
    // Try AMF info tool first
    out, err := exec.Command("amf-info").Output()
    if err != nil &#123;
        // Fall back to rocm-smi on Linux
        out, err = exec.Command("rocm-smi", "--showmeminfo", "vram", "--json").Output()
        if err != nil &#123;
            return nil, err
        &#125;
    &#125;
    // parse output ...
    return info, nil
&#125;

func probeIntel() (*GPUInfo, error) &#123;
    out, err := exec.Command("vainfo", "--display", "drm").Output()
    if err != nil &#123;
        return nil, err
    &#125;
    // parse output ...
    return info, nil
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h3>Runtime Monitoring</h3>
  <p>
    During encoding the agent samples GPU metrics every <code>gpu.monitor_interval</code> (default 5s) and includes them in heartbeat payloads sent to the controller.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Vendor</th><th>Metric</th><th>Source</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>NVIDIA</td><td>Utilisation %, VRAM used/total, temperature °C, power W</td><td><code>nvidia-smi --query-gpu=utilization.gpu,memory.used,memory.total,temperature.gpu,power.draw --format=csv,noheader,nounits</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>AMD</td><td>Utilisation %, VRAM used/total, temperature °C</td><td><code>rocm-smi --showuse --showmeminfo vram --showtemp --json</code> (Linux) / AMF SDK query (Windows)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Intel</td><td>Render engine utilisation %, memory used</td><td><code>intel_gpu_top -J -s 1000</code> (Linux) / IGCL SDK query (Windows)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Security</h2>

  <h3>mTLS Bootstrap</h3>
  <p>
    Certificate issuance happens during the <code>register</code> command, before the agent service is started for the first time:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>The agent generates a 2048-bit RSA or P-256 ECDSA key pair locally.</li>
    <li>It sends a Certificate Signing Request (CSR) to the controller's enrollment endpoint, authenticated by the one-time enrollment token.</li>
    <li>The controller signs the CSR with its internal CA and returns the signed certificate plus the CA certificate.</li>
    <li>The agent stores the certificate, key, and CA in its config directory. The enrollment token is discarded.</li>
    <li>All subsequent gRPC connections use this certificate for mutual TLS. The controller verifies the agent certificate against the CA; the agent verifies the controller certificate against the same CA.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    Certificates have a configurable validity period (default 1 year). The agent automatically renews its certificate 30 days before expiry using the existing certificate for authentication.
  </p>

  <h3>UNC Path Validation (Go)</h3>
  <pre><code>// internal/agent/security/paths.go

// IsAllowedPath reports whether path is under one of the configured allowed shares.
// It normalises both sides to prevent path traversal attacks.
func IsAllowedPath(path string, allowedShares []string) bool &#123;
    // Normalise separators and resolve any . or .. components.
    // filepath.Clean does not resolve symlinks — symlink resolution
    // is intentionally skipped to avoid TOCTOU races.
    clean := filepath.Clean(path)

    for _, share := range allowedShares &#123;
        cleanShare := filepath.Clean(share)
        // Require the path to start with the share AND be followed by
        // a separator (or be exactly equal), preventing prefix spoofing
        // where \\nas\media2 would match against \\nas\media.
        if clean == cleanShare &#123;
            return true
        &#125;
        prefix := cleanShare + string(filepath.Separator)
        if strings.HasPrefix(clean, prefix) &#123;
            return true
        &#125;
    &#125;
    return false
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h3>Batch Script Sandboxing (Windows)</h3>
  <p>
    On Windows, encode scripts run inside <code>cmd.exe /D /C</code>. The <code>/D</code> flag disables <code>AutoRun</code> registry commands, preventing system-wide <code>HKLM\...\AutoRun</code> entries from injecting commands into the encoder process. The agent also strips the inherited environment and rebuilds it with only:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>PATH</code> — limited to the tools directory and system32</li>
    <li><code>TEMP</code> / <code>TMP</code> — set to the job's <code>tmp/</code> subdirectory</li>
    <li>Template variables (e.g. <code>INPUT_PATH</code>, <code>OUTPUT_PATH</code>, <code>CRF</code>)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>No user tokens, credentials, or network drive mappings are inherited by the encoder process.</p>

  <h2>Logging &amp; Diagnostics</h2>

  <h3>Task Logs</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>File</th><th>Contents</th><th>Location</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>stdout.log</code></td><td>Full encoder stdout (progress lines + info messages)</td><td><code>&#123;log_dir&#125;/&#123;job_id&#125;/stdout.log</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>stderr.log</code></td><td>Full encoder stderr (warnings and errors)</td><td><code>&#123;log_dir&#125;/&#123;job_id&#125;/stderr.log</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>agent.log</code></td><td>Agent-level events for this job (state transitions, validation results)</td><td><code>&#123;log_dir&#125;/&#123;job_id&#125;/agent.log</code></td></tr>
