  "output":  "/mnt/nas/media/output/movie.hevc.mkv"
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h3>Health Endpoint</h3>
  <p>
    The agent exposes a lightweight HTTP health endpoint on <code>localhost:8081</code> (not accessible from the network by default). The controller polls this from the same host during smoke tests and post-upgrade validation.
  </p>
  <pre><code>GET http://localhost:8081/health

&#123;
  "status":    "ok",
  "version":   "1.2.3",
  "uptime_s":  3721,
  "state":     "ENCODING",
  "job_id":    "a3f8c1d2-...",
  "gpu": &#123;
    "vendor":       "nvidia",
    "util_pct":     87,
    "vram_used_mb": 3412,
    "vram_total_mb": 8192,
    "temp_c":        71
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h2>Upgrade Strategy</h2>
  <p>
    The controller can push a new agent binary to all (or selected) agents without manual intervention.
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Trigger</strong> — An administrator clicks <strong>Upgrade</strong> in the Agents UI, or calls <code>POST /api/v1/agents/&#123;id&#125;/upgrade</code>. The request specifies the target version.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Download</strong> — The agent downloads the new binary from the controller's internal artifact endpoint over the existing mTLS gRPC connection (no internet access required on the agent).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Verification</strong> — The agent verifies the SHA-256 checksum of the downloaded binary against the value published by the controller. If the checksum does not match, the upgrade is aborted and the event is logged.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Staged swap</strong> — The agent writes the new binary to <code>&#123;binary&#125;.new</code> next to the running binary, then sends itself a graceful shutdown signal. The service manager (Windows SCM or systemd) restarts the service, which now uses the new binary. On Linux, the service unit uses <code>ExecStartPre</code> to atomically <code>mv &#123;binary&#125;.new &#123;binary&#125;</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Health check</strong> — After restart, the controller polls the agent's health endpoint. If the agent does not return <code>"status": "ok"</code> within 60 seconds, the controller marks the upgrade as failed and alerts the administrator. The agent itself does not auto-rollback; rollback is triggered manually via the UI or API.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Job safety</strong> — Upgrades are only initiated when the agent is in the <code>IDLE</code> state. If the agent is actively encoding, the upgrade request is queued and executed as soon as the current job completes.
    </li>
  </ol>

